Galapagos land iguanas diet consists mostly of opuntia cactus. Which is also their main source of water. They use their claws to remove as many spines as possible and they spit out any that may be left. They also eat the cactus flowers and fruits (prickly pears). In order to remove the spines from the fruit, they roll it against the ground with their snout.#galapagos #mocreptiles #iguanasofig #darwin #nature_photography #wildlifeofig #herping #reptilesofig #lizardsofig #wildlife_photography #natureofig #conolophus #reptilesofinstagram #lizardsofinstagram #lizard #lizards #wildlife #reptiles #herpetology #prehistoric #dinosaur #dinosaursofig #dinosaursofinstagram #jurassic #dragon #dragons #dragonsofig #dragonsofinstagram #dinosaurs #jurassicpark

Marine iguanas are the only lizards truly adapted to live in the sea.
They have very strong and sharp claws that helps them grab and walk through the rocks underwater, and a very powerful tail to swim and to help keep balance with the strong ocean currents.
These lizards can dive deeper than 90 feet, and hold their breath for around 30 minutes if needed.
Their diet consist mostly on algae that grow along rocky shores.
Since they feed underwater they ingest a large amount of saltwater, and have evolved specialized glands that remove salt from their blood. To avoid dehydration they sneeze out the salt from their nostrils without expelling water. 
Here I posted pictures of 3 different subspecies of Amblyrhynchus cristatus:
-A. c. hassi from Santa Cruz.
-A. c. albemarlensis from Isabela, larger in size than hassi, longer face horns and longer crest spikes.
-A. c. venustissimus from Floreana. Incredible pink/rusty colorations, specially in males. In breeding season, November-January they are even more colorful.

This was my fourth attempt to find Corytophanes cristatus in the wild. They are not the rarest reptiles, but not easy to find in most places where they occur. Finding this beauty was the result of 20 plus hours of hiking in tropical rainforests 🦟🪰inspecting almost every single branch and slim tree trunk I came across 😅 sometimes you wonder if they really are in the area where you are looking or is just a myth lol ...most people would believe it is insane to do all this to find a lizard. But for me... I just can't describe that feeling when I finally do... and that is why I don't give up. Polychrus gutturosus. Known as the canopy lizard, monkey tailed anole or Berthold's bush anole.
Despite their common names and appearance, Polychrus are not anoles. 
This genus consists of 8 species, all found in Central and South America.
Like anoles, they are also iguanids, but they are more closely related to the genus Enyalioides than Dactyloidae.
Their movements resemble a lot the ones of chamaeleons. P. gutturosus specifically are adapted to live in the rainforest canopy, but often come down to lower branches and bushes to hunt (specially in the rainy season), and females reach the ground to lay eggs.
Their diet consists mainly of invertebrates such as grasshoppers but they are also known to hunt on smaller lizards and to eat flowers and fruits.

Bothrops asper. Most commonly known as fer-de-lance, terciopelo or X.

This species occupies a wide range of habitats, specially rainforests of most central America, Colombia, Venezuela and Ecuador.
They are also commonly found in rural areas of these tropical countries.

The hemotoxic venom of this pit viper is responsible for most snake related human facilities in the American continent. This has earned them a reputation of "evil" creatures and are therefore often killed when found by locals.

The truth is, when left alone, like all snakes, they will mind their own business. Their bite is just a defense mechanism.

Most Bothrops bites occur by accident in rural areas where farmers come too close to them while working in the fields, or people trying to kill them, handle them, walking too close or even stepping on them by accident.

If you ever encounter a Bothrops or any snake when hiking outdoors, please leave them alone. 
They play such a significant role in the wild, and are crucial at controlling rodent populations in rural areas. #bothropsasper #snakesofig #mocreptiles

A very special find. Ecnomiohyla sukia. 

Endemic to Costa Rica, very little is known about the biology of these flying frogs, mainly due to their canopy habits and rarity. 
This is an oophagous species that breeds in canopy tree trunk cavities filled with rain water.
Females feed the tadpoles with infertile eggs. 
Males guard the fertile eggs and tadpoles.
 
The extra skin between their massive toes and limbs, and very powerful legs, enables this species to jump and glide for long distances between the canopy trees. 

This is a newly metamorphosed baby. 
I will be posting pictures of a large male we found.

Male Ecnomiohyla sukia. This individual has a rusty reddish coloration. But they can also be lighter grey/green to resemble lichens and moss. 
Females can reach 2.8 inches in length. Males 2.2 inches. 
Found in mountainous rainforests of Costa Rica at elevations between 1300 and 3300 ASL.

Can't even describe the efforts, persistence, mental and physical skills and of course luck involved in finding these canopy frogs.
I must give a special thanks to Stanley Salazar and his apprentice Jonatan Hernandez. They put some serious efforts in finding this species. Stanley is a pioneer in the research of Amphibians in Costa Rica, having also discovered a few species. There is absolutely no way to see these frogs without the help of these specialists.

Is always a joy to find these small dinosaurs. That helmet, the eyes, the behavior.... such a unique looking and prehistoric animal.

I never had luck finding them in prime habitat in Colombia. I then searched for them in Panama's Anton Valley in several occasions with no luck neither.
On August this year I went on a few hikes in the Gamboa rainforest. On my fourth attempt there, the day of my birthday, after 6 hours hiking and searching meticulously every single branch I came across, I finally saw my first wild Corytophanes on my way back to the car. Can't even describe the excitement :))
On my following attempt, a week later I found two in the same trail. The harder you try, the luckier you get!

During this trip in CR I looked for them a lot. They occur in most of the country rainforests, but I only managed to find them in the Sarapiqui region. And I saw a dozen in just two nights. Including this gorgeous and colorful big male in the first pics. They are not aquatic at all, but the ones I saw there were all in proximity to streams.

I really love the prehistoric looks of this species. Always a pleasure to see that helmet poking out from a branch from a distance 🤩 as you get closer to them, they rotate around the branch to hide. They have such a variety of patterns, colors and shape that I always look forward to see how the next one looks like :)

Central American bushmaster, locally known as mata buey (bull/ox killer), scientific name Lachesis stenophrys. 

These gigantic vipers can reach over 10 feet in length.
I love their prehistoric looks and scales.

Despite their intimidating looks, they have a very calm temperament when compared to most viper species such as Bothropa asper. They are rare and live mainly in primary forests of Nicaragua, Costa Rica and Panama. They are rarely encountered in rural areas. 

Unlike most viper species, Lachesis lay eggs.

Sharing here very special moment from this year. The first time I ever saw a marine iguana (Amblyrhynchus cristatus). A very simple phone picture that means so much to me. Taken in Santa Cruz at around 7am. Visiting Galapagos was a childhood dream :)
The first day I arrived in the evening which was torture lol I couldn't sleep from the excitement, so I started hiking at 5am towards a remote beach, away from the touristic spots. I decided that my first encounter with this species would not have been in a crowded beach. I witnessed an incredible sunrise, no humans around. Waiting for the sun to heat up those volcanic rocks a bit I finally saw this beautiful juvenile coming out from the rocks. Very well camouflaged, but I saw it from far and I approached it slowly. I didn't know if it would hide or run away. 
Once I was getting closer it seemed calm and curious, probably the first time he or she ever saw a human. And for me to see this incredible dinosaur 😊

This is my favorite memory from the Galapagos trip. And one of the most special moments of 2023.
After seeing the first marine iguana I started walking towards a large pile of lava rocks which had plenty of crevices facing the East sunrise. 
All of the sudden I saw something moving. It was the head of a hatchling marine iguana popping out a crevice. 
As I got closer more tiny godzilla faces were coming out from different crevices. There were at least 30 hatchlings, very curious about my presence. I stayed there for about an hour witnessing such spectacle.

Pristimantis carranguerorum. A species I had no idea it even existed until yesterday. Listed as "Endangered".
With very few observations, endemic to a small part of the Colombian eastern Andes chain.
I was very excited to see such tiny frog (this was smaller than a finger nail) last night, and today finding out how rare it is. 
Unlike most amphibians the main treat of the genus Pristimantis is not the chytrid fungus, but habitat loss.

I also saw a few cool bugs in these mountains. 
I don't know much about invertebrates, but I always found them super cool.
My interest in macro (initially focused on reptiles and amphibians) is definitively growing my curiosity towards bugs, most likely because is allowing me to see things my naked eye cannot.

That green insect (pics 5-7, if anyone knows the species, please let me know) was tiny, just a couple millimeters in length. While trying taking pictures of "her" I noticed she was running towards her eggs, and started displaying a defense behavior by going on top of the eggs and rotating her body.
Such little bug probably goes unnoticed 99% of the times to us. In an another dimension, is a colorful, bizarre and beautiful creature with some unique behavior, and a protective parent. 

The "bugs" world is way more diverse than ours. There is so much going on at those dimensions :)
